+# FruitClaw Network Optimization Notes
+
+Date: 2026-07-04
+
+This is a backlog note for future FruitClaw Wi-Fi and ESP-Hosted optimization.
+It records the current observed behavior, the likely bottlenecks, and the
+specific things to test later.  These are not completed fixes.
+
+## Observed Behavior
+
+On the FruitClaw alpha build, `ping 8.8.8.8` worked but showed high jitter and
+late packets:
+
+```text
+10 packets transmitted, 9 received, 10% packet loss
+rtt min/avg/max = 20.000/358.888/890.000 ms
+
+10 packets transmitted, 6 received, 40% packet loss
+rtt min/avg/max = 20.000/383.333/630.000 ms
+```
+
+The pattern included very fast replies mixed with delayed replies around
+`600-1000 ms`.  That does not look like the best achievable performance.  It
+looks more like a transport, scheduling, buffering, or Wi-Fi power-save issue
+than a hard limit of the board.
+
+## Current Known Knobs
+
+Current live build references:
+
+```text
+nuttx/.config
+nuttx/drivers/wireless/esp_hosted.c
+```
+
+Relevant current settings:
+
+```text
+CONFIG_ESP_HOSTED_SPI_FREQUENCY=5000000
+CONFIG_ESP_HOSTED_LPWORK=y
+CONFIG_IOB_NBUFFERS=24
+CONFIG_IOB_NCHAINS=24
+ESP_HOSTED_RX_WORK_DRAIN_LIMIT=8
+ESP_HOSTED_NETDEV_RX_QUOTA=4
+ESP_HOSTED_NETDEV_TX_QUOTA=2
+```
+
+The current transport is ESP-Hosted over SPI.  NuttX sees a normal `wlan0`
+network interface, but the Wi-Fi radio and firmware run on the ESP32-C6
+coprocessor.
+
+## Optimization Ideas To Validate
+
+### 1. Increase ESP-Hosted SPI Clock
+
+The current SPI frequency is only `5 MHz`:
+
+```text
+CONFIG_ESP_HOSTED_SPI_FREQUENCY=5000000
+```
+
+Test candidates:
+
+```text
+10 MHz
+20 MHz
+maybe higher if stable
+```
+
+Validation:
+
+- Boot reliably.
+- Join Wi-Fi reliably.
+- Ping gateway and `8.8.8.8`.
+- Run Telegram polling and MCP server at the same time.
+- Confirm no SPI errors, network stalls, or board hangs.
+
+If higher SPI clocks become unstable, keep the fastest clock that survives a
+repeatable soak test.
+
+### 2. Move ESP-Hosted RX Work Off LPWORK
+
+Current config:
+
+```text
+CONFIG_ESP_HOSTED_LPWORK=y
+```
+
+Hypothesis:
+
+Network RX work on LPWORK can be delayed by other lower-priority work.  That can
+show up as late ICMP replies, MCP stalls, or bursty Telegram behavior.
+
+Test:
+
+- Try the HPWORK variant if available.
+- Compare ping jitter with no FruitClaw services running.
+- Compare ping jitter with FruitClaw MCP and Telegram running.
+- Watch for regressions in boot stability and CPU starvation.
+
+### 3. Increase RX Drain And Netdev Quotas
+
+Current driver constants:
+
+```text
+ESP_HOSTED_RX_WORK_DRAIN_LIMIT=8
+ESP_HOSTED_NETDEV_RX_QUOTA=4
+ESP_HOSTED_NETDEV_TX_QUOTA=2
+```
+
+Hypothesis:
+
+Small RX/TX quotas may cause packet bursts to drain over several scheduler
+turns.  That could explain alternating fast and slow ping replies.
+
+Possible tests:
+
+```text
+RX drain: 8 -> 16 -> 32
+RX quota: 4 -> 8 -> 16
+TX quota: 2 -> 4 -> 8
+```
+
+Validation:
+
+- ICMP latency.
+- MCP tool response time.
+- Telegram long-poll coexistence.
+- Heap and IOB availability.
+- No starvation of DVI, audio, SD, or shell.
+
+### 4. Increase IOB Buffers And Chains
+
+Current config:
+
+```text
+CONFIG_IOB_NBUFFERS=24
+CONFIG_IOB_NCHAINS=24
+```
+
+Hypothesis:
+
+The current IOB pool may be too small for simultaneous MCP, Telegram polling,
+HTTP client, telnet, and other network activity.
+
+Possible tests:
+
+```text
+CONFIG_IOB_NBUFFERS=48
+CONFIG_IOB_NCHAINS=48
+```
+
+Then test larger values only if memory allows.
+
+Validation:
+
+- `/proc` IOB information, if available.
+- `free` before and after network load.
+- MCP and Telegram simultaneous traffic.
+- Long-running soak without deadlock or packet starvation.
+
+### 5. Check ESP32-C6 Wi-Fi Power Save
+
+Hypothesis:
+
+Wi-Fi power-save on the coprocessor may create periodic latency spikes.  This is
+especially suspicious when ping alternates between very low latency and almost
+one-second replies.
+
+Things to investigate:
+
+- Whether the ESP-Hosted MCU firmware enables station power-save by default.
+- Whether there is an RPC/control path to disable or reduce power-save.
+- Whether the ESP32-C6 firmware should be rebuilt with a no-power-save default
+  for FruitClaw operator mode.
+
+Validation:
+
+- Gateway ping before/after.
+- `8.8.8.8` ping before/after.
+- Telegram and MCP responsiveness while idle.
+
+### 6. Separate RF Problems From Board Problems
+
+Always test in this order:
+
+```sh
+ifconfig
+ping <router-ip>
+ping 8.8.8.8
+```
+
+Interpretation:
+
+- Bad router ping means the issue is local: board, ESP32-C6, SPI transport,
+  Wi-Fi link, power save, or scheduling.
+- Good router ping but bad `8.8.8.8` ping means the board path may be fine and
+  the issue is WAN, DNS, routing, or internet path.
+
+Also compare while FruitClaw services are stopped versus while MCP and Telegram
+are active.
+
+### 7. Reduce Background Load During Network Tests
+
+When measuring raw network behavior, try to avoid unrelated load:
+
+- DVI stress patterns.
+- Heavy SD writes.
+- Berry scripts.
+- MCP tool storms.
+- Telegram long polling.
+- Verbose debug logging.
+
+After raw behavior is understood, re-enable services and measure coexistence.
+
+### 8. Consider SDIO Later
+
+SPI should perform better than the current results, so first optimize SPI.
+
+For a larger future improvement, evaluate ESP-Hosted over SDIO if the board
+wiring and NuttX driver support make it practical.  SDIO would be a bigger
+architecture change and should not block FruitClaw alpha stabilization.
+
+## Suggested Test Matrix
+
+For each candidate change, record:
+
+```text
+Build date:
+UF2 sha256:
+ESP32-C6 firmware build:
+SPI clock:
+Workqueue mode:
+IOB buffers/chains:
+RX drain/quota:
+TX quota:
+FruitClaw services running:
+Gateway ping min/avg/max/loss:
+8.8.8.8 ping min/avg/max/loss:
+MCP smoke result:
+Telegram smoke result:
+Notes:
+```
+
+Minimum useful smoke:
+
+```sh
+ifconfig
+ping <router-ip>
+ping 8.8.8.8
+fruitclaw status
+fruitclaw telegram-test
+fruitclaw mcp-smoke
+```
+
+If there is no `fruitclaw mcp-smoke` command in the current build, use the
+Hermes MCP test from the host instead.
+
+## Acceptance Target
+
+This does not need desktop-class Wi-Fi performance, but it should be much better
+than the current alpha results.
+
+Target for a usable FruitClaw operator build:
+
+- Gateway ping: low packet loss, mostly stable latency.
+- Internet ping: no regular one-second stalls under idle conditions.
+- MCP and Telegram can run together without starving each other.
+- Network tuning does not regress DVI, RTTTL/audio, SD, NSH, telnet, or
+  watchdog/BOOTSEL recovery behavior.
+
