+# Fruit Jam HSTX DVI Diagnostic
+
+This profile is a minimal DVI signal diagnostic for Adafruit Fruit Jam RP2350.
+It is intentionally not a FruitClaw, LVGL, TRMNL client, network, USB host, or
+SD-card profile.
+
+Read the board-level timing note before using this profile to judge TRMNL
+display support:
+
+```text
+nuttx/boards/arm/rp23xx/adafruit-fruit-jam-rp2350/TRMNL_DVI_TIMING.md
+```
+
+The 2026-07-02 live probe result was that native 800x480 works on the tested
+monitor with the official Pico SDK 2.2.0 Fruit Jam board baseline and tight
+25.2 MHz timing:
+
+```text
+800 active, 8 front, 16 sync, 16 back  -> 840 total
+480 active, 5 front, 5 sync, 10 back   -> 500 total
+25.200 MHz pixel clock                 -> 60.000 Hz
+```
+
+The current `esp-hosted` TRMNL-ish native 800x480 setting at 31.5 MHz was tested
+and did not produce a visible image on this monitor.  Do not treat that as a
+valid hardware-proven TRMNL timing.
+
+It enables only the pieces needed to isolate the low-bit-depth TRMNL-style HSTX
+DVI path:
+
+- USB CDC NSH console
+- board bootguard and `bootsel` recovery helpers
+- PSRAM-backed user heap
+- HSTX DVI framebuffer `/dev/fb0`
+- `dvictrl` with boot-time autostart
+- 800x480 packed Y2 app framebuffer with RGB332 scanout
+
+Build with:
+
+```sh
+./tools/configure.sh -E -l -a ../apps adafruit-fruit-jam-rp2350:hstxdvi
+make -j8
+```
+
+Expected runtime checks:
+
+```sh
+dvictrl info
+dvictrl pattern
+```
+
+The profile exists to isolate monitor/timing/HSTX issues from the larger
+FruitClaw operator image.  As of this note, it is still a diagnostic profile:
+it uses a 25.2 MHz pixel clock, but the NuttX mode/profile work still needs to
+be aligned with the exact native 800x480 tight timing proven by the SDK 2.2.0
+probe artifacts.
