@@ -0,0 +1,80 @@
+# Adafruit Fruit Jam RP2350 LVGL
+
+This profile runs LVGL through the standard NuttX framebuffer backend.
+
+Expected display device:
+
+- `/dev/fb0`
+- 320x240 framebuffer
+- RGB565, 16 bits per pixel
+- 640-byte stride
+- DVI/HSTX output at 640x480 with 1x centered scanout
+- This avoids the chunky 2x framebuffer scaling, but leaves black borders.
+
+Build from the NuttX tree with the sibling apps checkout:
+
+```sh
+./tools/configure.sh -E -m -a ../apps adafruit-fruit-jam-rp2350:lvgl
+make -j$(sysctl -n hw.ncpu)
+```
+
+Flash only when the board is in BOOTSEL:
+
+```sh
+picotool info -a
+picotool load -x nuttx.uf2
+```
+
+From NSH:
+
+```sh
+ls /dev
+piousbhost hidstatus
+dvictrl info
+dvictrl pattern colorbars
+dvictrl start
+lvgldemo widgets &
+berry -e "import lv; lv.start(); print(lv.get_hor_res(), lv.get_ver_res()); lv.stop()"
+berry /examples/lvgl_smoke.be
+berry /examples/lvgl_counter.be
+```
+
+`lvgldemo` should use `/dev/fb0` through `CONFIG_LV_USE_NUTTX`.
+When `CONFIG_INPUT_KEYBOARD` is enabled, `lvgldemo` reads `/dev/kbd0`
+as an LVGL keypad device. Tab and Shift+Tab move focus, Enter activates,
+Escape cancels, and the arrow/Home/End keys navigate focused widgets.
+With a hardware keyboard configured, `lvgldemo` hides LVGL's on-screen
+keyboard so mouse-selected text fields can use the real keyboard.
+When `CONFIG_INPUT_MOUSE` is enabled, `lvgldemo` also reads `/dev/mouse0`,
+shows a small cursor, supports click/drag, and maps wheel movement to
+vertical scrolling.
+
+This profile also enables `CONFIG_INTERPRETERS_BERRY_LVGL`.  Berry scripts can
+`import lv` or use the preloaded global `lv` module.  The module initializes
+LVGL through the same NuttX framebuffer backend on `/dev/fb0`; it does not start
+DVI power itself, so keep the guarded runtime order of `dvictrl start` before
+running Berry LVGL examples.  The optional Berry mouse adapter reads
+`/dev/mouse0`.
+
+Do not enable `CONFIG_LV_USE_NUTTX_LCD` for this board unless a real
+`/dev/lcd0` device is added later.
+
+## Display Timing Note
+
+The TRMNL 800x480 bring-up found an important stability rule that also matters
+for LVGL work: the Fruit Jam clock plan should stay at VREG 1.30 V, `clk_sys`
+252 MHz, and HSTX 126 MHz, but picky HDMI panels should not scan out directly
+from PSRAM.  PSRAM is appropriate for large LVGL heaps, image assets, and
+application framebuffers; the live HSTX/DVI scanout buffer should be internal
+SRAM unless a profile has been soak-tested with `dvictrl info` showing stable
+frame gaps and zero DMA errors.
+
+For 800x480 grayscale/TRMNL, the stable profile uses
+`CONFIG_RP23XX_HSTX_DVI_SINGLE_SCANOUT_INTERNAL=y`.  For future higher
+resolution or animated LVGL profiles, start from the same timing discipline and
+only add front/back scanout or PSRAM scanout after measuring it on hardware.
+See the board timing note:
+
+```text
+nuttx/boards/arm/rp23xx/adafruit-fruit-jam-rp2350/TRMNL_DVI_TIMING.md
+```
